5539 /*
5540  * Arrays are ordered, integer-indexed collections of any object.
5541  *
5542  * Array indexing starts at 0, as in C or Java. A negative index is assumed
5543  * to be relative to the end of the array---that is, an index of -1 indicates
5544  * the last element of the array, -2 is the next to last element in the
5545  * array, and so on.
5546  *
5547  * == Creating Arrays
5548  *
5549  * A new array can be created by using the literal constructor
5550  * <code>[]</code>. Arrays can contain different types of objects. For
5551  * example, the array below contains an Integer, a String and a Float:
5552  *
5553  * ary = [1, "two", 3.0] #=> [1, "two", 3.0]
5554  *
5555  * An array can also be created by explicitly calling Array.new with zero, one
5556  * (the initial size of the Array) or two arguments (the initial size and a
5557  * default object).
5558  *
5559  * ary = Array.new #=> []
5560  * Array.new(3) #=> [nil, nil, nil]
5561  * Array.new(3, true) #=> [true, true, true]
5562  *
5563  * Note that the second argument populates the array with references to the
5564  * same object. Therefore, it is only recommended in cases when you need to
5565  * instantiate arrays with natively immutable objects such as Symbols,
5566  * numbers, true or false.
5567  *
5568  * To create an array with separate objects a block can be passed instead.
5569  * This method is safe to use with mutable objects such as hashes, strings or
5570  * other arrays:
5571  *
5572  * Array.new(4) { Hash.new } #=> [{}, {}, {}, {}]
5573  *
5574  * This is also a quick way to build up multi-dimensional arrays:
5575  *
5576  * empty_table = Array.new(3) { Array.new(3) }
5577  * #=> [[nil, nil, nil], [nil, nil, nil], [nil, nil, nil]]
5578  *
5579  * An array can also be created by using the Array() method, provided by
5580  * Kernel, which tries to call #to_ary, then #to_a on its argument.
5581  *
5582  * Array({:a => "a", :b => "b"}) #=> [[:a, "a"], [:b, "b"]]
5583  *
5584  * == Example Usage
5585  *
5586  * In addition to the methods it mixes in through the Enumerable module, the
5587  * Array class has proprietary methods for accessing, searching and otherwise
5588  * manipulating arrays.
5589  *
5590  * Some of the more common ones are illustrated below.
5591  *
5592  * == Accessing Elements
5593  *
5594  * Elements in an array can be retrieved using the Array#[] method. It can
5595  * take a single integer argument (a numeric index), a pair of arguments
5596  * (start and length) or a range. Negative indices start counting from the end,
5597  * with -1 being the last element.
5598  *
5599  * arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
5600  * arr[2] #=> 3
5601  * arr[100] #=> nil
5602  * arr[-3] #=> 4
5603  * arr[2, 3] #=> [3, 4, 5]
5604  * arr[1..4] #=> [2, 3, 4, 5]
5605  * arr[1..-3] #=> [2, 3, 4]
5606  *
5607  * Another way to access a particular array element is by using the #at method
5608  *
5609  * arr.at(0) #=> 1
5610  *
5611  * The #slice method works in an identical manner to Array#[].
5612  *
5613  * To raise an error for indices outside of the array bounds or else to
5614  * provide a default value when that happens, you can use #fetch.
5615  *
5616  * arr = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']
5617  * arr.fetch(100) #=> IndexError: index 100 outside of array bounds: -6...6
5618  * arr.fetch(100, "oops") #=> "oops"
5619  *
5620  * The special methods #first and #last will return the first and last
5621  * elements of an array, respectively.
5622  *
5623  * arr.first #=> 1
5624  * arr.last #=> 6
5625  *
5626  * To return the first +n+ elements of an array, use #take
5627  *
5628  * arr.take(3) #=> [1, 2, 3]
5629  *
5630  * #drop does the opposite of #take, by returning the elements after +n+
5631  * elements have been dropped:
5632  *
5633  * arr.drop(3) #=> [4, 5, 6]
5634  *
5635  * == Obtaining Information about an Array
5636  *
5637  * Arrays keep track of their own length at all times. To query an array
5638  * about the number of elements it contains, use #length, #count or #size.
5639  *
5640  * browsers = ['Chrome', 'Firefox', 'Safari', 'Opera', 'IE']
5641  * browsers.length #=> 5
5642  * browsers.count #=> 5
5643  *
5644  * To check whether an array contains any elements at all
5645  *
5646  * browsers.empty? #=> false
5647  *
5648  * To check whether a particular item is included in the array
5649  *
5650  * browsers.include?('Konqueror') #=> false
5651  *
5652  * == Adding Items to Arrays
5653  *
5654  * Items can be added to the end of an array by using either #push or #<<
5655  *
5656  * arr = [1, 2, 3, 4]
5657  * arr.push(5) #=> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
5658  * arr << 6 #=> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
5659  *
5660  * #unshift will add a new item to the beginning of an array.
5661  *
5662  * arr.unshift(0) #=> [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
5663  *
5664  * With #insert you can add a new element to an array at any position.
5665  *
5666  * arr.insert(3, 'apple') #=> [0, 1, 2, 'apple', 3, 4, 5, 6]
5667  *
5668  * Using the #insert method, you can also insert multiple values at once:
5669  *
5670  * arr.insert(3, 'orange', 'pear', 'grapefruit')
5671  * #=> [0, 1, 2, "orange", "pear", "grapefruit", "apple", 3, 4, 5, 6]
5672  *
5673  * == Removing Items from an Array
5674  *
5675  * The method #pop removes the last element in an array and returns it:
5676  *
5677  * arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
5678  * arr.pop #=> 6
5679  * arr #=> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
5680  *
5681  * To retrieve and at the same time remove the first item, use #shift:
5682  *
5683  * arr.shift #=> 1
5684  * arr #=> [2, 3, 4, 5]
5685  *
5686  * To delete an element at a particular index:
5687  *
5688  * arr.delete_at(2) #=> 4
5689  * arr #=> [2, 3, 5]
5690  *
5691  * To delete a particular element anywhere in an array, use #delete:
5692  *
5693  * arr = [1, 2, 2, 3]
5694  * arr.delete(2) #=> 2
5695  * arr #=> [1,3]
5696  *
5697  * A useful method if you need to remove +nil+ values from an array is
5698  * #compact:
5699  *
5700  * arr = ['foo', 0, nil, 'bar', 7, 'baz', nil]
5701  * arr.compact #=> ['foo', 0, 'bar', 7, 'baz']
5702  * arr #=> ['foo', 0, nil, 'bar', 7, 'baz', nil]
5703  * arr.compact! #=> ['foo', 0, 'bar', 7, 'baz']
5704  * arr #=> ['foo', 0, 'bar', 7, 'baz']
5705  *
5706  * Another common need is to remove duplicate elements from an array.
5707  *
5708  * It has the non-destructive #uniq, and destructive method #uniq!
5709  *
5710  * arr = [2, 5, 6, 556, 6, 6, 8, 9, 0, 123, 556]
5711  * arr.uniq #=> [2, 5, 6, 556, 8, 9, 0, 123]
5712  *
5713  * == Iterating over Arrays
5714  *
5715  * Like all classes that include the Enumerable module, Array has an each
5716  * method, which defines what elements should be iterated over and how. In
5717  * case of Array's #each, all elements in the Array instance are yielded to
5718  * the supplied block in sequence.
5719  *
5720  * Note that this operation leaves the array unchanged.
5721  *
5722  * arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
5723  * arr.each { |a| print a -= 10, " " }
5724  * # prints: -9 -8 -7 -6 -5
5725  * #=> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
5726  *
5727  * Another sometimes useful iterator is #reverse_each which will iterate over
5728  * the elements in the array in reverse order.
5729  *
5730  * words = %w[first second third fourth fifth sixth]
5731  * str = ""
5732  * words.reverse_each { |word| str += "#{word} " }
5733  * p str #=> "sixth fifth fourth third second first "
5734  *
5735  * The #map method can be used to create a new array based on the original
5736  * array, but with the values modified by the supplied block:
5737  *
5738  * arr.map { |a| 2*a } #=> [2, 4, 6, 8, 10]
5739  * arr #=> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
5740  * arr.map! { |a| a**2 } #=> [1, 4, 9, 16, 25]
5741  * arr #=> [1, 4, 9, 16, 25]
5742  *
5743  * == Selecting Items from an Array
5744  *
5745  * Elements can be selected from an array according to criteria defined in a
5746  * block. The selection can happen in a destructive or a non-destructive
5747  * manner. While the destructive operations will modify the array they were
5748  * called on, the non-destructive methods usually return a new array with the
5749  * selected elements, but leave the original array unchanged.
5750  *
5751  * === Non-destructive Selection
5752  *
5753  * arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
5754  * arr.select { |a| a > 3 } #=> [4, 5, 6]
5755  * arr.reject { |a| a < 3 } #=> [3, 4, 5, 6]
5756  * arr.drop_while { |a| a < 4 } #=> [4, 5, 6]
5757  * arr #=> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
5758  *
5759  * === Destructive Selection
5760  *
5761  * #select! and #reject! are the corresponding destructive methods to #select
5762  * and #reject
5763  *
5764  * Similar to #select vs. #reject, #delete_if and #keep_if have the exact
5765  * opposite result when supplied with the same block:
5766  *
5767  * arr.delete_if { |a| a < 4 } #=> [4, 5, 6]
5768  * arr #=> [4, 5, 6]
5769  *
5770  * arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
5771  * arr.keep_if { |a| a < 4 } #=> [1, 2, 3]
5772  * arr #=> [1, 2, 3]
5773  *
5774  */
